alternatives.transcript: Hi there. This is Chris. And in this video, I'm going to show you how to log on to the Myth computers from a Linux computer. And I happen to be running Ubuntu. You can this will work for any flavor of Unix or Linux that you have. In Ubuntu, I can click up here to actually find the terminal program. So you need to be able to open the terminal. And when I open up the terminal program, I'll make it a little bit bigger here. When I open up the terminal program to actually log on to the myth computers, type s s h for secure shell and then your SUNET ID, mine happens to be c greg and then at miff dot stanford dot edu and in fact if you're on the Stanford campus you don't even need to type the stanford. Part, you can just type c greg at miff and then when you log on the first time it will ask you if you're sure you wanna continue, you will answer yes. And then, it will never ask you that again actually. But it does ask you for your password. Now, if I type my password in here, you'll notice as I'm typing it that, it is not showing up on the screen and that's just a security method, a security measure so that you, nobody can look over your shoulder when you're typing your password. But rest assured you could be typing and your password is going into the, computer. And then you're logged in and so that's about it. If we there's some other commands, I happen to have a one zero seven directory which we can c d into and you can type your commands like l s etcetera. A couple commands you might wanna know just basically being in the terminal are clear, which clears the screen, and then reset, which also clears the screen but in a slightly lower level. And, how do you log out of the NIF computers? You just type log out and then enter or you can type control d and that will also log you out. Thanks.
